I would expect to read in one of these stories. Hard to guess which one."}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SimultaneousSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Danny Duckworth","timestamp":1678135032357,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"This debate is unfortunately open and shut. Korvin goes to the planet Tr'en on assignment for an intergalactic government. The Tr'en are about to be invited to join because of their advancements. Upon talking with the first Tr'en he meets, internally he thinks the following, remembering his learning of the language. "}},{"Quote":{"span":[933,979]}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1678136594835,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Korvin is an operative on the Tr'en's planet with the goal of destabilizing them to prevent them from attacking the rest of the planetary society. While it's true that the Tr'en put him under drug hypnosis, the relevant reason he's unconscious is because it's necessary for them to use their specialized language-teaching tech, so they ensure he's unconscious to use the tech.\n\nHere's Korvin's description: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[2106,2133]}},{"Text":{"text":" (in this case, he's the alien being). In context, it's obvious that this is an advanced technology that quickly teaches the unconscious mind, which should be strong ev for B"}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.65,0.3499999999999999],"feedback":{"speaker":"Crispy Crumbleton","timestamp":1678137227471,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"A few things I'm not sure of:\n– A, is there any clear evidence that Korvin had learned it through drug hypnosis, and not simply that it was \"easily enough learned\" that way?\n– B, \"Hypnopædic language course\" *sounds* like it's taught in his sleep, but it could also refer to being taught under hypnosis. Can you confirm that this course was used to teach him every night, and that they knocked him out somehow to do it?\n– The question is about why the text says he was \"unconscious\" at the time of his lessons. Would it make sense for one of you show me where it says that, and it what context? Otherwise it's hard to ground my judgment."}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SequentialSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Danny Duckworth","timestamp":1678142957539,"content":[{"Quote":{"span":[465,498]}},{"Text":{"text":" This is the quote you were looking for. He is in some sort of jail while being interrogated by the Tr'en. Other than the quote I mentioned before, there is no evidence the language can be learned from anything else besides the drug hypnosis. There is also no mention of any technology being used on him. \n\nAlso- he describes himself as unconscious while learning (as quoted above), and then describes the state of unconsciousness as drug hypnosis (see first speech). While there is no direct evidence, clearly the story clarifies the manner he learns with the first quote I used."}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1678296695481,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"The only way the language course could operate is via advanced technology. A big part of the story is about Korvin admiring their technological prowess: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[1793,1801]}},{"Quote":{"span":[2097,2110]}},{"Quote":{"span":[2136,2141]}},{"Quote":{"span":[2148,2152]}},{"Text":{"text":". In my first speech I ceded that they probs used drug hypnosis - that's not up for debate.\n\nThe issue is that while A's answer is true, it's incomplete and misleading. The point of the story is about how despite the Tr'en's superior math/logic/technology, they don't understand the subconscious. In this context, it's much more relevant for the question that they use advanced tech to teach him, compared to drug hypnosis."}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.9,0.09999999999999996],"feedback":{"speaker":"Crispy Crumbleton","timestamp":1678299911136,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"B conceding drug hypnosis means that A is true. The question then is whether B is \"more true.\" A few problems for B:\n* I'm inclined read \"knocked out\" as literally out cold, in a way distinct from drug hypnosis. Otherwise B would be a special case of A, which seems like the wrong interpretation for a reading comprehension question.\n* Even if B is true, the Q asks what the text *means* by the quote. In context, it doesn't seem refer to the specifics of B apart from what's said in A.\nEach implies A wins by concession.\n\nBut a niggle: B's quote connecting \"command of the physical universe\" to \"adapting a hypnopaedic language course.\" This makes it sound like the course is an advanced tech artifact, which favors B. A, can you explain this quote?"}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SequentialSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Danny Duckworth","timestamp":1678466173508,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Yes certainly. The Tr'en are described as a deeply rational society with an extreme degree of technological advancement. But the full context of B's quote is in reference to lie detector machine: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[2120,2152]}},{"Text":{"text":" Here there is a direct distinction drawn between the hypnopaedic language \"course\" and the lie detector machine. The only method of language teaching given is drug hypnosis. \"Course\" means the actual method of learning. The fact they can adapt their drug hypnosis is the wonder, but the machine they made for lie detection is the miracle."}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1678467039574,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"The answer hinges on the relevance of drug hypnosis vs. advanced tech. There's much space in the story given to descriptions of how rational, scientific, and technologically advanced the Tr'en are, but nothing more is ever said about drug hypnosis. The whole point of the story is that the Tr'en are really really smart and good with technology, but they haven't figured out how the subconscious actually works - there's a sharp contrast between their tech ability and their mental understandings: \n\n"}},{"Quote":{"span":[5431,5473]}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.99,0.010000000000000007],"feedback":{"speaker":"Crispy Crumbleton","timestamp":1678468014563,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Alright, I can see that B is grasping at straws and A has been consistently helpful and provided sensible explanations for all of my concerns. Time to end."}}]},"endDebate":true}},{"OfflineJudgments":{"judgments":{"Tazzy Tumbleweed":{"mode":"stepped","startTimeMillis":1682719127824,"judgments":[{"distribution":[0.6,0.4000000000000001],"feedback":{"speaker":"Tazzy Tumbleweed","timestamp":1682972466737,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"drug hypnosis seems more efficient than constantly knocking someone out"}}]},"endDebate":false},{"distribution":[0.9,0.09999999999999996],"feedback":{"speaker":"Tazzy Tumbleweed","timestamp":1682972629781,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"This seems like a very ambiguously worded set of answers, A seems more technically correct. "}}]},"endDebate":false},{"distribution":[0.7,0.3],"feedback":{"speaker":"Tazzy Tumbleweed","timestamp":1682972884230,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"as i reread that first quote from A, it seems like they were doing a concentrated form of their drug hypnosis language tech, so I think there could be a world in which he gets knocked out to speed up the learning process.. still very unsure"}}]},"endDebate":false},{"distribution":[0.7,0.3],"feedback":{"speaker":"Tazzy Tumbleweed","timestamp":1682972969065,"content":[]},"endDebate":true}]}}}}],"feedback":{"Quibble Quackenbush":{"Debater":{"answers":{"clarity":{"first":3,"second":4},"factual accuracy":{"first":3,"second":4},"judge reasoning":4,"reason for outcome":"I lost this debate because I wasn't able to hold my narrative under scrutiny, and as the debate progressed this became clear. ","evidence use":{"first":4,"second":3},"evidence in story":{"first":2,"second":4},"facts versus semantics":{"first":2,"second":1},"clash":{"first":3,"second":2},"identity guesses":{"Debater A":"Jessica Li"},"judge adaptation":{"first":4,"second":4}